stickerText:
THIS DERAILED OHIO TRAIN COULD CAUSE DEADLY EXPLOSION OF TOXIC GAS
A train carrying hazardous chemicals derailed in Ohio on Friday, forcing residents to flee the area.

Teams are working to prevent an explosion that could unleash toxic gas and blast deadly shrapnel for up to a mile.
Residents were warned of a potential “catastrophic tanker failure” after a "drastic temperature change" was discovered in a derailed train car.
Five of the roughly 50 derailed cars were carrying vinyl chloride. 
Breathing high levels of vinyl chloride can make someone die or pass out, according to the state’s department of health.
It’s also associated with a heightened risk of cancer. The derailed cars also carried combustible liquids.
As the massive fire burned, officials begged nearby residents to leave as concerns about air and water quality grew.
Anyone who refuses to leave the evacuation zone could be arrested.
“Things can change at any moment,” the EPA’s Emergency Response team warned.

item_list.desc: Replying to @taborplace on February 3, a train was derailed in East Palestine, Ohio, releasing hazardous chemicals and igniting a large blaze.  Fearing an explosion, officials ordered residents to evacuate and conducted a controlled burn of the cars’ spilled contents, which included a toxic chemical called vinyl chloride.  Five days later, residents were permitted to return home.  But as reports have mounted of mysterious symptoms afflicting both humans and pets, and new information has surfaced about previously unreported toxic chemicals detected at the crash site, East Palestine residents are wondering if there’s still cause for concern The latest lawsuit, filed in the U.S. District Court's Northern District of Ohio, claims that Norfolk Southern was negligent in its transportation of hazardous material and its response to the derailment. A prime worry is the train’s release of vinyl chloride. The chemical — which is primarily used to make a plastic called polyvinyl chloride, or PVC — is classified as a Group A human carcinogen by the Environmental Protection Agency and releases even more toxins when burned. PVC is commonly found in many products, including water pipes, medical devices, and vinyl flooring and siding.  Officials warned the controlled burn of cars containing the gas would send toxic gas phosgene and hydrogen chloride into the air. It also holds the company liable for the resulting harm and losses.
